		{"id":"ce6214fefa3a6c97","type":"file","file":"Teaching/Intro to abstract mathematics/Bits/Numbers/Shepherd knowledge.md","x":-550,"y":-335,"width":400,"height":470},
		{"id":"efe9a1f9e82470fd","type":"file","file":"Teaching/Intro to abstract mathematics/Bits/Numbers/Scaling up the flock.md","x":50,"y":-270,"width":450,"height":490},
		{"id":"0060b41fa4086cd4","type":"file","file":"Teaching/Intro to abstract mathematics/Bits/Numbers/The shepherd start.md","x":-1360,"y":-145,"width":400,"height":270},
		{
			"id":"3a41e79ba44a411f",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"Natural numbers as a direct counting approach: counting on fingers\n\nImagine you are a shepherd.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-560,
			"y":1400,
			"width":300,
			"height":140
		},
		{
			"id":"05d530fd7c0d4428",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"Counting a specific category of objects",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-80,
			"y":1440,
			"width":260,
			"height":60
		},
		{
			"id":"ce2b6bcc4f5cb017",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"Addition on natural numbers",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":360,
			"y":1440,
			"width":260,
			"height":60
		},
		{
			"id":"d87ead7a0fcd307e",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"The successor operation as the defining property of numbers",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":-410,
			"y":1800,
			"width":260,
			"height":100
		},
		{
			"id":"dc5776678c4ea77c",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"There are several cognitive leaps that happened here:\n1. A single stone doesn't represent a concrete sheep anymore.\n2. We assumed that, if we keep the pouch intact and no sheep get lost, then, independently on the order of stones and order of sheep, we will get the same answer to the question \"Are there any sheep missing?\"\n3. As a consequence, there is something in common between the flock of sheep and the pouch of stones that does not depend on the objects themselves and is only reflective of the amount of objects. The concept of number is not verbalized yet, but the tokenization is an experimental belief in the *existence* of numbers.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":210,
			"y":720,
			"width":660,
			"height":300
		},
		{"id":"1e42e17ad3d2a059","type":"file","file":"Teaching/Intro to abstract mathematics/Bits/Numbers/The birth of addition.md","x":540,"y":-840,"width":400,"height":400},
		{
			"id":"cc82f716bf1f9ad2",
			"type":"text",
			"text":"You can’t just look at the pile of sheep. You have to verify.\nYou line up your stones. You ask your neighbor to line up his sheep.\n\nYou pair them off:\n- Stone 1 $\\leftrightarrow$ Sheep 1\n- Stone 2 $\\leftrightarrow$ Sheep 2\n- ...\n\nIf every stone has a sheep, and every sheep has a stone, and nothing is left over, you are satisfied.",
			"styleAttributes":{},
			"x":1320,
			"y":-200,
			"width":380,
			"height":350
		},
		{"id":"d09e2f2ffb5c6fe2","type":"file","file":"Teaching/Intro to abstract mathematics/Bits/Numbers/Checking the flock.md","x":1320,"y":-640,"width":380,"height":410}
	],
